1
00:00:02,569 --> 00:00:07,704
<i>- It's not fair! It's my money!
- I know. But it's what Bread wanted.</i>

2
00:00:08,181 --> 00:00:10,746
- Okay, which one is she?
- That's Bread's widow.

3
00:00:10,981 --> 00:00:12,089
And why's she so upset?

4
00:00:12,324 --> 00:00:14,177
Because she just found out
she was cut out of the will.

5
00:00:14,481 --> 00:00:17,437
Doesn't she know you can't define
yourself in terms of money?

6
00:00:17,772 --> 00:00:19,729
That it's about values and morals...

7
00:00:19,764 --> 00:00:22,388
...and your ability
to give and receive love?

8
00:00:23,530 --> 00:00:24,324
No.

9
00:00:25,693 --> 00:00:28,655
<i>- Oh, Drake.
- I'm sorry, Amber.</i>

10
00:00:28,905 --> 00:00:31,492
<i>It's like Brad to have
to have the last word.</i>

11
00:00:32,492 --> 00:00:34,035
Sorry I'm late.
What happened?

12
00:00:34,285 --> 00:00:35,578
We wanna see the end.

13
00:00:35,829 --> 00:00:37,122
<i>I want you, Drake.</i>

14
00:00:37,372 --> 00:00:38,498
<i>I know you do.</i>

15
00:00:38,748 --> 00:00:41,292
<i>But we can never
be together that way.</i>

16
00:00:41,543 --> 00:00:42,377
<i>What?</i>

17
00:00:42,627 --> 00:00:44,712
<i>There's something I never told you.</i>

18
00:00:44,963 --> 00:00:49,259
<i>I'm actually your half-brother.</i>

19
00:00:53,138 --> 00:00:54,723
So what happens next?

20
00:00:54,973 --> 00:00:58,268
I get the medical award
for separating the Siamese twins.

21
00:00:58,518 --> 00:01:03,815
Then Amber and I go to Venezuela
to meet our other half-brother, Ramon...

22
00:01:04,065 --> 00:01:07,819
...where I find the world's
biggest emerald. It's really big.

23
00:01:08,069 --> 00:01:10,363
But it's cursed.

24
00:01:10,613 --> 00:01:11,406
So cool!

25
00:01:11,656 --> 00:01:15,034
God, that is good TV!

26
00:01:15,785 --> 00:01:18,913
The One Where Dr. Ramoray Dies

27
00:02:03,683 --> 00:02:06,519
Pheebs, play with me!

28
00:02:06,769 --> 00:02:08,104
This game is grotesque!

29
00:02:08,354 --> 00:02:12,358
Twenty armless guys joined
at the waist by a steel bar...

30
00:02:12,608 --> 00:02:15,861
...forced to play soccer forever?

31
00:02:16,112 --> 00:02:18,781
Hello? Human rights violation!

32
00:02:19,031 --> 00:02:21,200
Don't feel so bad.
After playing...

33
00:02:21,450 --> 00:02:26,956
...I break out the plastic women
and everybody has a good time.

34
00:02:26,956 --> 00:02:30,710
Why don't you play with your roommate?

35
00:02:30,793 --> 00:02:32,712
He's not a big fan of foosball.

36
00:02:32,962 --> 00:02:35,631
Are we not getting along
with the new boy?

37
00:02:35,881 --> 00:02:39,802
No, he's all right. He spends
most of his time in his room.

38
00:02:40,052 --> 00:02:42,555
That's because you haven't
gotten to know him.

39
00:02:42,805 --> 00:02:44,599
Let's remedy that, shall we?

40
00:02:44,849 --> 00:02:48,352
- We don't need to.
- It'll be fun!

41
00:02:50,229 --> 00:02:52,607
What was that?

42
00:02:52,940 --> 00:02:57,069
I thought it'd be fun if we had
beers and got to know each other.

43
00:02:57,320 --> 00:02:58,154
All right.

44
00:02:58,404 --> 00:03:00,031
Oh, good! Okay.

45
00:03:00,281 --> 00:03:04,744
Oh, no! I have to go,
because I'm late for...

46
00:03:04,994 --> 00:03:08,623
...my <i>Green Eggs and Ham</i>
discussion group.

47
00:03:08,998 --> 00:03:12,376
Tonight, it's "Why he would not
eat them on a train."

48
00:03:12,627 --> 00:03:14,754
- Have fun! Bye!
- That was so lame.

49
00:03:15,004 --> 00:03:16,964
I know.

50
00:03:17,214 --> 00:03:20,092
Okay, talk to him.

51
00:03:22,428 --> 00:03:29,101
So you think that <i>Speed Racer</i> guy
gets a lot of tickets or...?

52
00:03:30,519 --> 00:03:32,897
That's good.
So who broke up with who?

53
00:03:33,147 --> 00:03:34,273
I broke up with her.

54
00:03:34,523 --> 00:03:39,237
She actually thought Sean Penn
was the capital of Cambodia.

55
00:03:39,487 --> 00:03:44,325
When everybody knows that
the capital of Cambodia is...

56
00:03:44,909 --> 00:03:47,203
It's not Sean Penn.

57
00:03:47,453 --> 00:03:48,746
I got a funny one.

58
00:03:48,996 --> 00:03:52,500
My last girlfriend, Tilly.
We're eating breakfast, right?

59
00:03:52,750 --> 00:03:55,086
I made these pancakes.
Like, 50 pancakes.

60
00:03:55,336 --> 00:03:58,381
All of a sudden,
she turns to me and says, "Eddie...

61
00:03:58,631 --> 00:04:00,550
...I don't wanna see you anymore."

62
00:04:00,800 --> 00:04:03,678
It was literally like she had
reached into my chest...

63
00:04:03,928 --> 00:04:08,182
...ripped out my heart
and smeared it all over my life!

64
00:04:08,432 --> 00:04:11,352
There was this incredible abyss
and I'm falling.

65
00:04:11,602 --> 00:04:16,857
I keep falling and
I don't think I'm ever gonna stop!

66
00:04:19,652 --> 00:04:23,197
That wasn't such a funny story.

67
00:04:27,368 --> 00:04:29,745
<i>And a crusty old man
Said I'll do what I can</i>

68
00:04:29,996 --> 00:04:33,875
<i>And the rest of the rats
Played maracas</i>

69
00:04:35,001 --> 00:04:38,754
That's it! Thanks! Good night.

70
00:04:38,963 --> 00:04:42,174
Phoebe's got another job, right?

71
00:04:42,425 --> 00:04:44,135
Great set tonight, Pheebs.

72
00:04:44,385 --> 00:04:46,304
I know.

73
00:04:46,554 --> 00:04:48,389
We should get going.

74
00:04:48,639 --> 00:04:51,392
We should too.
I've got patients at 8 in the morning.

75
00:04:51,642 --> 00:04:53,895
You know how we always stay
at your apartment?

76
00:04:54,145 --> 00:04:56,647
I thought tonight
we'd stay at my place.

77
00:04:56,898 --> 00:05:00,610
I don't know.
I don't have my jammies.

78
00:05:00,610 --> 00:05:02,236
You don't need them.

79
00:05:02,486 --> 00:05:06,574
My baby sister, ladies and gentlemen.

80
00:05:06,782 --> 00:05:09,410
Shut up. I'm happy.

81
00:05:09,952 --> 00:05:13,206
Oh, this is so nice!
I have to make a speech.

82
00:05:13,456 --> 00:05:19,670
Of all the guys that Monica has
been with, and that is a lot...

83
00:05:20,463 --> 00:05:23,090
...I like you the best.

84
00:05:23,341 --> 00:05:26,260
Thank you, Pheebs.
That's very sweet.

85
00:05:26,511 --> 00:05:27,678
You hear that?

86
00:05:27,929 --> 00:05:32,975
She likes me best. And apparently,
there have been a lot.

87
00:05:33,184 --> 00:05:34,352
Not a lot.

88
00:05:34,602 --> 00:05:38,606
Phoebe's kidding. Phoebe's crazy.

89
00:05:38,815 --> 00:05:42,151
Phoebe's dead.

90
00:05:47,782 --> 00:05:49,700
I'm looking for Eddie Manoick.

91
00:05:49,951 --> 00:05:52,203
He's not here right now.
I'm Chandler.

92
00:05:52,453 --> 00:05:55,248
Can I take a message or...
Or a fish tank?

93
00:05:55,498 --> 00:05:56,916
Thanks.

94
00:05:57,166 --> 00:05:58,668
Come on in.

95
00:05:58,918 --> 00:06:01,504
I'm Tilly.

96
00:06:06,425 --> 00:06:09,053
I gather by that "Oh,"
he told you about me.

97
00:06:09,303 --> 00:06:12,140
Yeah, your name came up...

98
00:06:12,390 --> 00:06:17,019
...in a conversation that
terrified me to my very soul.

99
00:06:17,270 --> 00:06:18,604
He's kind of intense.

100
00:06:18,855 --> 00:06:21,607
Yes! Hey, can I ask you,
is Eddie a little...

101
00:06:21,858 --> 00:06:22,733
A little what?

102
00:06:22,984 --> 00:06:26,070
...bit country?

103
00:06:27,098 --> 00:06:28,099
Or...

104
00:06:29,114 --> 00:06:30,765
You know, a little rock 'n' roll?

105
00:06:32,713 --> 00:06:35,049
Come on in, you roomie!

106
00:06:35,299 --> 00:06:36,592
Hello, Tilly.

107
00:06:36,842 --> 00:06:39,470
Eddie, I just came by
to drop off your tank.

108
00:06:39,720 --> 00:06:41,597
That was very thoughtful of you.

109
00:06:41,847 --> 00:06:44,934
It's very thoughtful.

110
00:06:47,728 --> 00:06:49,730
Well, okay then.

111
00:06:49,981 --> 00:06:53,484
I'm gonna go. Bye.

112
00:06:56,362 --> 00:06:58,030
So we getting a fish?

113
00:06:58,281 --> 00:07:01,033
You had sex with her.

114
00:07:03,744 --> 00:07:05,371
Check it out, check it out!

115
00:07:05,621 --> 00:07:11,002
<i>Soap Opera Digest</i>!
That's one of my favorite digests!

116
00:07:11,252 --> 00:07:15,298
Page 42! Page 42!

117
00:07:15,798 --> 00:07:19,510
"New Doc on the Block,
<i>Days of our Lives</i> Joey Tribbiani."

118
00:07:19,760 --> 00:07:21,804
Cool picture!

119
00:07:22,054 --> 00:07:25,266
Oh, I look good.

120
00:07:25,391 --> 00:07:29,103
Is this true? That you write
a lot of your own lines?

121
00:07:29,353 --> 00:07:31,898
Well, kind of, yeah.

122
00:07:32,148 --> 00:07:35,026
Remember last week
when Alex was in the accident?

123
00:07:35,276 --> 00:07:37,028
The line in the script was...

124
00:07:37,278 --> 00:07:40,740
..."If we don't get this woman
to a hospital, she's going to die."

125
00:07:40,990 --> 00:07:43,951
But I made it, "If this woman
doesn't get to a hospital...

126
00:07:44,202 --> 00:07:47,663
...she's not gonna live."

127
00:07:47,747 --> 00:07:52,752
Oh, okay.
I see what you did there.

128
00:07:53,711 --> 00:07:59,258
Aren't you afraid the writers will be
kind of mad when they read this?

129
00:07:59,467 --> 00:08:05,348
I never thought about the writers.
The scripts just come to my house.

130
00:08:06,724 --> 00:08:08,059
But you know what?

131
00:08:08,309 --> 00:08:11,729
This makes me look good,
which makes the show look good...

132
00:08:11,979 --> 00:08:16,901
...which makes the writers look good.
So how could they be mad?

133
00:08:17,151 --> 00:08:19,153
<i>Makes up most of his lines.</i>

134
00:08:19,403 --> 00:08:22,198
<i>Son of a...</i>

135
00:08:23,616 --> 00:08:25,368
<i>Write this, jerk-weed.</i>

136
00:08:25,618 --> 00:08:27,328
I fall down an elevator shaft?

137
00:08:27,578 --> 00:08:30,498
What does this mean?
I fall down an elevator shaft?

138
00:08:30,748 --> 00:08:35,753
I don't know.
I just bring the scripts.

139
00:08:35,753 --> 00:08:39,257
They can't kill me!
I'm Francesca's long-lost son!

140
00:08:39,507 --> 00:08:42,134
Right.

141
00:08:42,385 --> 00:08:43,386
Could you sign?

142
00:08:43,636 --> 00:08:46,514
No! No way! I'm not signing that!

143
00:08:46,764 --> 00:08:51,018
I don't think that will affect
the plot of the show.

144
00:08:51,269 --> 00:08:55,022
How can they do this to me?

145
00:08:56,440 --> 00:08:59,277
All right, I'm just gonna go.

146
00:08:59,527 --> 00:09:02,113
Sorry.

147
00:09:06,826 --> 00:09:08,911
Well, it wasn't that many guys.

148
00:09:09,162 --> 00:09:12,206
If you consider how many guys
there actually are...

149
00:09:12,457 --> 00:09:14,792
...it's a very small percentage.

150
00:09:15,042 --> 00:09:17,795
It's not that big a deal.
I was just curious.

151
00:09:18,045 --> 00:09:19,714
- Good night.
- Good night, Richard.

152
00:09:19,964 --> 00:09:21,757
Good luck, Mon.

153
00:09:22,008 --> 00:09:27,805
Before I tell you, you tell me
how many women you've been with.

154
00:09:28,473 --> 00:09:29,474
Two.

155
00:09:29,724 --> 00:09:32,768
Two? Two?

156
00:09:33,019 --> 00:09:35,104
How is that possible? I mean...

157
00:09:35,354 --> 00:09:38,983
...have you seen you?

158
00:09:39,567 --> 00:09:40,902
I mean, what can I say?

159
00:09:41,152 --> 00:09:45,323
I was married to Barbara for 30 years,
my high-school sweetheart.

160
00:09:45,573 --> 00:09:47,950
Now you. That's two.

161
00:09:48,201 --> 00:09:50,453
Two it is.

162
00:09:50,703 --> 00:09:53,790
Time for bed.
I'm gonna brush my teeth.

163
00:09:54,040 --> 00:09:55,666
No, wait a minute now!

164
00:09:55,917 --> 00:09:57,627
Come on, it's your turn.

165
00:09:57,877 --> 00:10:00,713
Oh, come on!

166
00:10:00,963 --> 00:10:05,885
You know, I don't need the
actual number. Just a ballpark.

167
00:10:06,135 --> 00:10:10,723
Okay, it is definitely
less than a ballpark.

168
00:10:14,018 --> 00:10:16,395
I am so glad
I'm not Monica right now.

169
00:10:16,646 --> 00:10:18,314
Tell me about it.

170
00:10:18,564 --> 00:10:22,735
So what's your magic number?

171
00:10:23,945 --> 00:10:28,616
Come on, you know everyone
I've been with. All both of them.

172
00:10:28,866 --> 00:10:31,452
Well, there's you.

173
00:10:31,702 --> 00:10:34,997
Better not be doing these in order.

174
00:10:35,873 --> 00:10:39,293
Billy Dreskin, Pete Carny.

175
00:10:39,544 --> 00:10:41,754
Barry.

176
00:10:42,004 --> 00:10:42,922
Paolo.

177
00:10:43,172 --> 00:10:47,760
Oh, yes, the weenie from Turinie.

178
00:10:48,052 --> 00:10:51,597
Honey, are you jealous of Paolo?

179
00:10:51,848 --> 00:10:55,435
I'm so much happier with you
than I ever was with him.

180
00:10:55,685 --> 00:10:57,729
- Really?
- Oh, please!

181
00:10:57,979 --> 00:11:01,065
That Paolo thing was
barely a relationship.

182
00:11:01,315 --> 00:11:06,446
All it really was
was just meaningless, animal sex.

183
00:11:08,990 --> 00:11:14,704
Okay, you know, that sounded
so much better in my head.

184
00:11:14,954 --> 00:11:17,123
I didn't sleep with
your ex-girlfriend.

185
00:11:17,373 --> 00:11:20,668
That's exactly what someone
who slept with her would say.

186
00:11:20,918 --> 00:11:24,005
This is nuts! Crazy!
She came over for two minutes...

187
00:11:24,255 --> 00:11:26,507
...dropped off a fish tank and left!

188
00:11:26,758 --> 00:11:27,925
Where's Buddy?

189
00:11:28,176 --> 00:11:29,218
Buddy?

190
00:11:29,469 --> 00:11:31,721
My fish, Buddy.

191
00:11:31,971 --> 00:11:34,223
There was no fish
when she dropped it off.

192
00:11:34,474 --> 00:11:36,601
This is unbelievable!

193
00:11:36,851 --> 00:11:40,855
You sleep with my ex-girlfriend,
insult my intelligence by lying...

194
00:11:41,105 --> 00:11:43,191
...then you kill my fish?
My Buddy?

195
00:11:43,441 --> 00:11:45,068
I didn't kill your fish!

196
00:11:45,318 --> 00:11:48,654
Look, Eddie...

197
00:11:50,531 --> 00:11:52,992
Would you look at what I'm doing?

198
00:11:53,242 --> 00:11:56,287
Now that can't be smart.

199
00:11:58,331 --> 00:12:01,292
So we're just gonna
take this guy right off you...

200
00:12:01,542 --> 00:12:05,546
...and put him here in Mr. Pocket.

201
00:12:06,089 --> 00:12:08,966
Tangelo?

202
00:12:16,484 --> 00:12:20,571
That's it? That's the giant number
you were afraid to tell me?

203
00:12:20,821 --> 00:12:22,865
Well, that's not bad at all.

204
00:12:23,115 --> 00:12:26,994
You had me thinking it was,
like, a fleet.

205
00:12:27,244 --> 00:12:28,245
You're okay with it?

206
00:12:28,496 --> 00:12:31,749
Oh, honey, I'm fine.

207
00:12:34,919 --> 00:12:36,962
Okay, about that two.

208
00:12:37,213 --> 00:12:38,255
What?

209
00:12:38,506 --> 00:12:40,132
All right.

210
00:12:40,382 --> 00:12:41,509
What about my two?

211
00:12:41,759 --> 00:12:44,345
It just seems like
a really small number.

212
00:12:44,595 --> 00:12:47,181
Right.

213
00:12:48,474 --> 00:12:51,852
Don't you have a lot
of wild oats to sow?

214
00:12:52,102 --> 00:12:57,066
Or is that what you're doing with me?
Oh, my God! Am I an oat?

215
00:12:57,316 --> 00:12:59,026
Honey, you are not an oat.

216
00:12:59,276 --> 00:13:03,030
I don't know, I guess
I'm just not an oat guy.

217
00:13:03,280 --> 00:13:05,616
I've only slept with women I love.

218
00:13:05,866 --> 00:13:09,161
You've only slept with two people.

219
00:13:12,623 --> 00:13:15,126
Right.

220
00:13:21,632 --> 00:13:24,343
You know I love you too, right?

221
00:13:24,593 --> 00:13:27,763
Now I do.

222
00:13:32,101 --> 00:13:34,687
Ross, please listen to me.

223
00:13:34,937 --> 00:13:37,940
You are so much better for me
than Paolo ever was.

224
00:13:38,190 --> 00:13:41,235
You care about me, you're loving,
you make me laugh.

225
00:13:41,485 --> 00:13:43,946
If I make you laugh, here's an idea.

226
00:13:44,196 --> 00:13:46,282
Invite Paolo to have
a romp in the sack...

227
00:13:46,532 --> 00:13:51,120
...and I'll stand in the corner
and tell knock-knock jokes!

228
00:13:53,080 --> 00:13:56,083
What we have is special!
All Paolo and I ever had was...

229
00:13:56,333 --> 00:13:59,044
"Animal sex"?

230
00:14:00,880 --> 00:14:02,548
So what are you saying?

231
00:14:02,798 --> 00:14:05,676
There's nothing between us
"animal" at all?

232
00:14:05,926 --> 00:14:09,847
There's not even,
like, a little animal?

233
00:14:10,097 --> 00:14:11,807
Not even, like...

234
00:14:12,057 --> 00:14:14,852
...chipmunk sex?

235
00:14:17,062 --> 00:14:19,815
Try to hear me, okay?

236
00:14:20,065 --> 00:14:22,526
I'm not gonna lie to you.

237
00:14:22,777 --> 00:14:27,615
- It was good with Paolo.
- Knock-knock.

238
00:14:28,324 --> 00:14:31,285
But what you and I have
is so much better.

239
00:14:31,535 --> 00:14:35,831
We have tenderness,
we have intimacy, we connect.

240
00:14:36,082 --> 00:14:37,541
You know? I swear.

241
00:14:37,792 --> 00:14:39,877
This is the best...

242
00:14:40,127 --> 00:14:44,340
...I have ever had.

243
00:14:44,423 --> 00:14:46,842
Until now.

244
00:14:54,016 --> 00:14:55,518
Richard told me he loved me.

245
00:14:55,768 --> 00:14:56,852
- Oh, my God!
- I know!

246
00:14:57,103 --> 00:14:58,396
Honey, that's great!

247
00:14:58,646 --> 00:14:59,814
I know!

248
00:15:00,064 --> 00:15:01,732
- I just can't find...
- Top drawer.

249
00:15:01,982 --> 00:15:06,195
- Hurry.
- Why? You need one too?

250
00:15:07,113 --> 00:15:10,032
Found them!

251
00:15:13,202 --> 00:15:15,663
There's only one.

252
00:15:17,456 --> 00:15:22,878
We'll be right there.
We're just trying to decide something.

253
00:15:39,437 --> 00:15:44,358
- They're trying to decide something.
- Good. Good, good.

254
00:15:49,113 --> 00:15:54,869
So was your mustache...
Did it used to be different?

255
00:16:00,416 --> 00:16:05,004
How do you, you know,
keep it so neat?

256
00:16:05,421 --> 00:16:07,840
I have a comb.

257
00:16:11,135 --> 00:16:12,928
- What is that?
- A mustache comb.

258
00:16:13,179 --> 00:16:15,639
Thank you.

259
00:16:15,890 --> 00:16:21,270
Okay, I will do your laundry
for one month.

260
00:16:22,271 --> 00:16:23,898
I will, I will, I will...

261
00:16:24,148 --> 00:16:26,817
I will clean the apartment
for two months.

262
00:16:27,068 --> 00:16:32,865
I'll give this to you now, if you
tell me where we keep the dustpan.

263
00:16:41,082 --> 00:16:44,251
So were you in Nam?

264
00:16:47,237 --> 00:16:51,250
Okay. You know what?
We are both adults here. Right?

265
00:16:51,285 --> 00:16:53,231
There has gotta be
a mature way to handle this.

266
00:16:53,838 --> 00:16:56,382
- Rock, paper, scissors?
- Gotcha.

267
00:16:56,632 --> 00:16:58,384
One, two, three.

268
00:16:58,634 --> 00:17:01,304
Yes!

269
00:17:01,554 --> 00:17:05,224
Fine. Go have sex.

270
00:17:06,142 --> 00:17:08,478
No! You have got it completely wrong!

271
00:17:08,728 --> 00:17:11,564
John Savage was <i>Deer Hunter</i>,
no legs.

272
00:17:11,814 --> 00:17:14,650
Jon Voight was <i>Coming Home</i>,
couldn't feel his legs.

273
00:17:14,901 --> 00:17:19,030
You've got it totally the other way
around, my friend. Jon Voight...

274
00:17:19,280 --> 00:17:22,617
- Honey?
- What?

275
00:17:29,707 --> 00:17:30,500
Shall we?

276
00:17:30,750 --> 00:17:32,168
It's not gonna happen.

277
00:17:32,418 --> 00:17:37,215
They're doing it tonight.
We can do it tomorrow.

278
00:17:38,674 --> 00:17:43,471
In the future, if I could see
the schedule beforehand...

279
00:17:45,723 --> 00:17:47,475
So when I woke up this morning...

280
00:17:47,725 --> 00:17:51,103
...he'd stolen all the insoles
out of my shoes!

281
00:17:51,354 --> 00:17:52,146
Why?

282
00:17:52,396 --> 00:17:56,234
He thinks I slept with his
ex-girlfriend and killed his fish.

283
00:17:56,484 --> 00:17:59,821
Why would you kill his fish?

284
00:18:01,697 --> 00:18:04,367
Because sometimes
after you sleep with someone...

285
00:18:04,617 --> 00:18:08,496
...you have to kill a fish.

286
00:18:09,080 --> 00:18:10,498
Chandler, honey...

287
00:18:10,748 --> 00:18:11,833
...I'm sorry.

288
00:18:12,083 --> 00:18:14,669
Can we watch Joey's show now, please?

289
00:18:14,919 --> 00:18:16,420
Wait. He's not here yet.

290
00:18:16,671 --> 00:18:19,757
He knows what happens.

291
00:18:20,174 --> 00:18:24,137
I'm fine about my problem now,
by the way.

292
00:18:25,805 --> 00:18:27,432
<i>Amber...</i>

293
00:18:27,682 --> 00:18:30,059
<i>...I'll always be there for you...</i>

294
00:18:30,309 --> 00:18:32,812
<i>...as a friend and as your brother.</i>

295
00:18:33,062 --> 00:18:35,064
<i>Oh, Drake.</i>

296
00:18:35,314 --> 00:18:36,607
<i>Hard day, huh?</i>

297
00:18:36,858 --> 00:18:39,527
First the medical award, now this?

298
00:18:39,777 --> 00:18:43,072
Some guys are just lucky, I guess.

299
00:18:43,322 --> 00:18:47,994
<i>Dr. Ramoray, report to
first floor Emergency stat.</i>

300
00:18:48,744 --> 00:18:50,788
Well, then...

301
00:18:51,038 --> 00:18:54,292
...I guess that's me.

302
00:18:55,209 --> 00:18:59,672
Anyone else need to go on the elevator?
Dr. Horton? Dr. Wall?

303
00:18:59,922 --> 00:19:03,384
They only said you.

304
00:19:04,093 --> 00:19:06,679
Oh, okay. All right.

305
00:19:06,929 --> 00:19:08,097
I love you.

306
00:19:08,347 --> 00:19:10,600
Yeah, whatever.

307
00:19:10,850 --> 00:19:11,851
Oh, no!

308
00:19:12,101 --> 00:19:14,979
Drake, look out!

309
00:19:18,066 --> 00:19:21,903
- Did they just kill off Joey?
- No!

310
00:19:22,820 --> 00:19:26,074
Now maybe.

311
00:19:26,074 --> 00:19:29,077
Come on! Open up!
We want to talk to you!

312
00:19:29,327 --> 00:19:30,745
I don't feel like talking!

313
00:19:30,995 --> 00:19:32,872
Come on! We care about you.

314
00:19:33,122 --> 00:19:38,795
- We're worried about you.
- And some of us really have to pee!

315
00:19:41,422 --> 00:19:44,467
I'm sorry, Joey.

316
00:19:45,051 --> 00:19:48,930
Listen, sorry about your death.
That really sucks.

317
00:19:49,180 --> 00:19:52,475
- We came over as soon as we saw.
- How could you not tell us?

318
00:19:52,725 --> 00:19:57,688
I don't know. I was kind of hoping
no one would ever find out.

319
00:19:57,939 --> 00:20:01,776
Well, maybe they could find
a way to bring you back.

320
00:20:02,026 --> 00:20:06,364
They said that when they found my body,
my brain was so smashed in...

321
00:20:06,614 --> 00:20:11,744
...that the only doctor
who could've saved me was me.

322
00:20:11,953 --> 00:20:15,790
It's supposed to be
some kind of irony.

323
00:20:16,207 --> 00:20:17,875
But Joey, you're gonna be fine.

324
00:20:18,126 --> 00:20:21,504
You don't need that show.
It was just a dumb soap opera.

325
00:20:21,754 --> 00:20:24,882
This was the greatest thing
that ever happened to me.

326
00:20:25,133 --> 00:20:29,011
Yes! I was going to incorporate that.

327
00:20:29,262 --> 00:20:33,891
Here's Monica.
She'll have something nice to say.

328
00:20:33,933 --> 00:20:38,563
I straightened out your shower curtain
so you won't get mildew.

329
00:20:38,813 --> 00:20:41,691
What? To me, that's nice.

330
00:20:41,941 --> 00:20:44,193
It'll be okay. You know that.

331
00:20:44,444 --> 00:20:47,155
No, I don't.

332
00:20:47,405 --> 00:20:50,700
It's like you work
your whole life for something...

333
00:20:50,950 --> 00:20:53,077
...and you think
that when you get it...

334
00:20:53,327 --> 00:20:55,621
...it'll never be
as good as you thought.

335
00:20:55,872 --> 00:20:57,749
But this so was.

336
00:20:57,999 --> 00:20:59,542
It changed everything.

337
00:20:59,792 --> 00:21:03,004
Like, the other day,
I got this credit card application...

338
00:21:03,254 --> 00:21:07,091
...and I was pre-approved!

339
00:21:08,092 --> 00:21:11,429
I've never been pre-approved
for anything in my life!

340
00:21:11,679 --> 00:21:13,181
I'm sorry, man.

341
00:21:13,431 --> 00:21:16,684
I don't know if this'll mean
anything to you...

342
00:21:16,934 --> 00:21:20,605
...but you'll always be
pre-approved with us.

343
00:21:20,855 --> 00:21:24,067
That means nothing to me.

344
00:21:29,781 --> 00:21:33,159
Pecan sandy? Just made them.

345
00:21:33,242 --> 00:21:36,204
Yeah, all right.

346
00:21:36,454 --> 00:21:38,498
Are these raisins?

347
00:21:38,748 --> 00:21:41,125
Sure, why not?

348
00:21:47,006 --> 00:21:49,884
Listen, Eddie.

349
00:21:49,926 --> 00:21:53,346
I've been thinking about
our living situation.

350
00:21:53,596 --> 00:21:54,722
Why are you smiling?

351
00:21:54,973 --> 00:21:58,643
I got a little surprise.
Look. There's a new fishy.

352
00:21:58,893 --> 00:22:00,186
I named him...

353
00:22:00,436 --> 00:22:04,524
...Chandler, you know, after you.

354
00:22:12,156 --> 00:22:15,952
Well, that's not even a real fish.

355
00:22:16,202 --> 00:22:20,206
No, that's a Goldfish cracker.

356
00:22:20,540 --> 00:22:23,751
So what's your point, man?

357
00:22:26,379 --> 00:22:28,923
Okay, good night.

358
00:22:29,173 --> 00:22:33,136
You big freak of nature!

359
00:22:58,303 --> 00:23:01,306
- Brisk tonight.
- Oh, man.

360
00:23:01,557 --> 00:23:05,602
- Let's never speak of this.
- You got it.
